**Tech stack:** Claude Sonnet API (speed + structured JSON output), LangGraph (cyclic graphs, conditional edges, parallel fan-out), Python 3.12 + FastAPI (async + WebSocket), React + Vite + TailwindCSS (real-time UI), Python dict with context-aware retrieval logic (MVP memory), WebSocket (full-duplex streaming). MCP is layered on top only after direct paths are proven stable.

**Scalability design (architecture beyond the demo):** Memory: Python dict → Redis/Valkey (1:1 interface, the MemoryStore.write/get_context methods stay identical). Execution: asyncio.gather() → Celery/Ray distributed workers. Orchestration: LangGraph local → LangGraph Cloud with persistent checkpoints and resumability. Tools: direct Python calls → MCP servers (already designed as optional layer). History: in-memory → PostgreSQL for debate analytics and plan quality tracking over time. None of this is built for the demo — it is architected for so the path from demo to production is clear.

**Ecosystem thinking:** The system is designed for extensibility at every layer. API surface: POST /api/v1/tasks (submit), GET /api/v1/tasks/{id} (status/result), WS /api/v1/tasks/{id}/stream (real-time pipeline), GET /api/v1/tasks/{id}/debate (transcript), GET /api/v1/tasks/{id}/memory (MMA snapshot), DELETE /api/v1/tasks/{id} (cancel). Extension points: custom EA rubrics (swap the EA's system prompt and sub-score weights for domain-specific evaluation — e.g., "prioritize security" for code tasks), agent type registry (add new AGENT_TEMPLATES entries with system prompts and tool configs), webhook callbacks for Slack/CI/CD post-completion notifications. When MCP is enabled, any compliant tool server plugs in without adapters and third-party MCP agents can join as sub-agents.

## Features

- **Adversarial Debate Loop** — DA proposes plan, EA stress-tests through 2–3 rounds. EA returns structured EACritique with four sub-scores (completeness, coherence, efficiency, dependency_correctness) weighted into confidence. Threshold ≥ 0.8 to approve. Hard cap at 3 rounds. Each round streamed live via WebSocket. The key demo moment: watching the EA's critique visibly change the DA's plan between rounds, with sub-scores shifting — proof that adversarial debate adds substantive value.
- **Plan-Driven Dynamic Agent Spawning** — Sub-agents created at runtime via prompt generation pipeline with explicit AgentConfig interface. SubTask.agent_type → template, .description → instruction, .output_schema → response format, .depends_on → MMA context preload, .tools_needed → tool binding. Never predefined. Pipeline code is auditable.
- **Context-Aware Shared Memory (MMA)** — Two retrieval mechanisms: dependency-graph routing (only predecessor outputs, not entire store) and schema-aware extraction (filter fields to match requesting agent's output_schema). Prevents context bloat. Maintains coherence. Store is Python dict; retrieval logic is the contribution.
- **Real-Time Streaming UI** — Debate rounds with DA proposals and EA critiques side-by-side, sub-score bars updating per round, agent spawning with configs visible, execution progress, memory flow arrows between agents, final result with provenance. Focus: make the plan-change moment between debate rounds unmissable.
- **MCP-Native Tool & Memory Interface (Optional Layer)** — Direct Python function calls are the primary path. MCP is layered on top for interoperability. Sub-agents can access tools via MCP servers when enabled. MMA can expose memory as MCP resources. Demo runs clean without MCP.
- **LangGraph State Machine** — 6-node cyclic graph: dynamic_agent → evaluator_agent (conditional: revise/approved) → task_decomposer → sub_agent_executor → memory_manager → assembler → END.
- **Structured JSON Contracts** — All agents use typed TypedDict models with strict validation. EACritique includes sub_scores dict. AgentConfig is the shared interface between spawning and MMA. Invalid outputs caught before MMA writes.
- **Dependency-Aware Execution** — SubTask.depends_on fields define the execution graph. Independent tasks run in parallel via asyncio.gather(). Dependent tasks wait for predecessors, receive filtered context from MMA.

